<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910328-0059</DOCNO><DOCID>910328-0059.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Japan's NEC Corp. Unveils   Its Wireless Notebook PC</HL><DATE>03/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   IBM NIPNY</CO><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- NEC Corp. launched a portable machine that blendsthe functions of personal computers and cellular phones.   The wireless, notebook-sized machine, the first commercialproduct in an untapped market expected to draw several majorcomputer makers in the next few months, weighs threekilograms and allows users to send and receive data withoutthe inconvenience of plugging into an ordinary telephonenetwork.</LP><TEXT>   The PC went on sale only in Japan, although officials saidthey will consider overseas sales.   In a separate news conference earlier in the day,International Business Machines Corp. showed off its firstnotebook-sized computer at its Tokyo headquarters acrosstown. IBM's machine will also sell just in Japan, at leastfor now, to study market support. It weighs 2.5 kilograms anddifferent versions sell for between 232,000 yen ($1,672) and368,000 yen. IBM-Japan will make 10,000 notebook PCs a month.   NEC's initial sales expectations for its RadioCommunications-9801 are quite modest: about 5,000 units inthe first year. The price is a hefty 548,000 yen -- abouthalf of that covering the cost of the built-intelecommunications device -- and users will also have to pay9,100 yen up front plus 2,400 yen a month to subscribe to awireless phone service.   The PCs send data to teleterminals placed throughoutTokyo, which in turn relay the data to a host computer.Another PC subscribing to the system can retrieve the data,via a teleterminal, from the host computer.</TEXT></DOC>